public abstract class MySuperClass implements ListDelegation{ 
   private final List mylist; // This is our delegated instance. It's a reference of the superclass 'List'.   
     public void add() {mylist.add();}     
       @Override       
         public void remove(){mylist.remove(); }         
           MySuperClass(final  List list){this. mylist = (List) list;} // Constructor to set the delegated instance  
    abstract class Stack extends MySuperClass {     protected final static int MAX_SIZE;      private Object[] elements ;       public void push(){elements[++top]=item} ... }       
```  In this way, you can use delegate methods in your superclass and still have access to the delegated instance. This is a common technique used when dealing with complex inheritance hierarchies where one class needs an interface or abstract base for other classes but doesn't want/need all of its functionality directly available through that parent-interface (or higher level).

